The book's paratactic echoes are many--of 'Pepe the Frog,' 'D.I.Y.,' Zen, collage cinema, jumper cables, the 'Tank-Top Walla & the Puppet-Flayers,' The P där a Bums of Chucky, The Night of the Living Dead, parataxical criticism, El sentido común, and Google Translate.
- Tom Beckett
As a volume of poetry . . . The text testifies to a engagé poetics, and to the reader as witness, participant. Its leaps of imagination, its dizzying pace and strategy, and its matrix of associations in metaphor . . . are a sharpened practice. It's an aesthetic written from barretrunning and contemporary realities, from complexity, irony, and honesty.

Kent Johnson's poetics here amounts to nearly fifty years of struggle against media-generated torture and multiple atrocities . . . constructed with aJohn Cage-like use of random procedures . . .
Michael Drews, editor of Verse
The charge of Kent Johnson's T.E.H. is of the most vibrant, vertiginous sort: it demands immediate attention. - Vincent Cellucci, author of Fluids & Assorted Intoxications
T.E.H. is an erratic alphabet that thinks America begins in the mind with the child's first steps, a break, a push, a line, a sometimes unspeakable fear, an image of Batman, a thirty-five year-old mother, blueprints as bedsheets, sleep as sobremesa, the daily dinner conversations of family. T.E.H. is art as artifacts, sitting on top of Auggie Wren, regarding his reflection, holding the surface tension of a pool of water, tearing the-self-apart, tearing-the-self-apart-and-back-together, tearing-the-self-apart-and-back-together-again.
- Charles Deice, author of Divining Underwater Dreams
